speech.p:
asked the Minister of Agriculture (1) whether he is aware that a 14-year old Warwick boarder pupil, working under the Ministry's scheme, was injured through no fault of his own, resulting in a lost eye, and that he has not received compensation; and will he remedy this with a view to encouraging parents and boys to co-operate with the scheme in the future;

(2) whether he is aware that the courts have recently held there was no necessity for schools to make arrangements for supervision of any description when sending out parties of boys under the Schoolboy Farming Scheme; that the parents' permission regarding the scheme is not necessary; and, as such conditions are not

conducive to the future success of the scheme, will he take steps to get these conditions altered?

Resolved, That the Orders made by the Secretary of State for the Home Department under the Sunday Entertainments Act, 1932, extending Section 1 of the Act to—
(1) The Borough of Wenlock (certain parts);
(2) The Urban District of Barnard Castle;
(3) The Urban District of Hay; and
(4) The Sandown Ward of the Urban District of Sandown-Shanklin,
copies of which were presented to this House on 20th January, be approved."—[Mr. Peake.]
